{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471846"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/877"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.13,0.03,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48783"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/877"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"565"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48783"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of vomiting green material and poor feeding. He has not yet passed meconium. He has no significant medical history and was born at term via normal vaginal delivery. He is not on any medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 50/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The abdomen is generally distended. Initial ultrasound shows malposition of the superior mesenteric arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hirschsprung disease","Meconium ileus","Small bowel atresia","Pyloric stenosis","Midgut volvulus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic picture of \u003Cstrong\u003Emidgut volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as volvulus neonatorum. The key features are bilious vomiting, abdominal distension, and failure to pass meconium in a neonate. The ultrasound finding of malposition of the superior mesenteric arteries is highly suggestive of this diagnosis. Other characteristic ultrasound findings in midgut volvulus include duodenal dilatation with a tapering configuration and the \u0027whirlpool sign\u0027. It\u0027s crucial to note that bilious vomiting in neonates should be assumed to be due to volvulus until proven otherwise, as this condition has a high mortality rate without urgent surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyloric stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with non-bilious projectile vomiting and is usually seen in slightly older infants (3-6 weeks). The vomiting in this case is bilious, making pyloric stenosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel atresia\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly, but the ultrasound findings would be different. Duodenal atresia, for instance, is characteristically associated with a \u0022double-bubble\u0022 sign on abdominal ultrasound or x-ray. In more distal atresia, there may be an air-fluid level proximal to the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/strong\u003E involves an absence of neural ganglion cells extending proximally from the anus. While it can cause abdominal distension and failure to pass meconium, bilious vomiting would not typically be a predominant feature. On abdominal X-ray, the proximal colon would be distended with narrowing of the rectum. Diagnosis is confirmed by full-thickness rectal biopsy showing aganglionosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeconium ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with cystic fibrosis (CF) in over 90% of cases. This would typically be detected on the newborn screening test (Guthrie test) performed at 48 hours of age. Given the acute presentation and the ultrasound findings, meconium ileus is unlikely to be the cause of obstruction in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Volvulus neonatorum is recognised on ultrasound by duodenal dilatation, malposition of the superior mesenteric vessels and the whirlpool sign.","Bilious vomiting in neonates should be assumed to be due to volvulus until proven otherwise.","Midgut volvulus requires urgent surgical intervention due to its high mortality rate."],"references":["Abramo T, Ahrens W, Aks S, Arpilleda J, Atabaki S, Barata I et al. Pediatric Emergency Medicine. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2011.","Weinberger E, Winters W, Liddell R, Rosenbaum D, Krauter D. Sonographic diagnosis of intestinal malrotation in infants: importance of the relative positions of the superior mesenteric vein and artery. American Journal of Roentgenology. 1992;159(4):825-828."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"877"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-16T18:54:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-13T15:41:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"